05233nam a22008655i 9781487542603DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875426037 a10.3138/97814875426032doi  a(DE-B1597)618937  a(OCoLC)1285970268  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a851.41 aMigiel, Marilyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVeronica Franco in Dialogue /cMarilyn Migiel. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Italian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on the Text and Translations of Veronica Franco’s Terze rime (Poems in Terza Rima) -- tIntroduction: What Do We See in Veronica Franco? -- t1 Gendered Strategies of Persuasion: Terze rime 1 and 2 -- t2 Poetic Identity and Community: Terze rime 3 and 4 -- t3 Repenting as a Courtesan: Terze rime 5 and 6 -- t4 Complaining and Cognitive Reframing: Terze rime 7 and 8 -- t5 Seductive Insinuation and Obliquely Frank Refusal: Terze rime 9 and 10 -- t6 Verona, Venezia, Veronica: Terze rime 11 and 12 -- t7 Attacks and Concessions under Erasure: Terze rime 13 and 14 -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the late twentieth century, the Venetian courtesan Veronica Franco has been viewed as a triumphant proto-feminist icon: a woman who celebrated her sexuality, an outspoken champion of women and their worth, and an important intellectual and cultural presence in sixteenth-century Venice. In Veronica Franco in Dialogue, Marilyn Migiel provides a nuanced account of Franco’s rhetorical strategies through a close analysis of her literary work. Focusing on the first fourteen poems in the Terze Rime, a collection of Franco’s poems published in 1575, Migiel looks specifically at back-and-forth exchanges between Franco and an unknown male author. Migiel argues that in order to better understand what Franco is doing in the poetic collection, it is essential to understand how she constructs her identity as author, lover, and sex worker in relation to this unknown male author. Veronica Franco in Dialogue accounts for the moments of ambivalence, uncertainty, and indirectness in Franco’s poetry, as well as the polemicism and assertions of triumph. In doing so, it asks readers to consider their ideological investments in the stories we tell about early modern female authors and their cultural production.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aItalian authors.  aItalian intellectual life.  aItalian poetry.  aItaly.  aRenaissance poetry.  aTerze rime.  aVenetian.  aVenice.  aVeronica Franco.  acourtesan.  aearly modern.  asixteenth century literature.  awomen’s literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754260340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487542603423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487542603/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  